 and thus sounded very much like the German verb hat (has). Long o’s with him inevitably became short ones: his “no” sounded positively Italian, and this was accentuated by his trick of triplicating the simple negative (“May I give you a lift, Mr. Pnin?” “No-no-no, I have only two paces from here”). He did not possess (nor was he aware of this lack) any long oo: all he could muster when called upon to utter “noon” was the lax vowel of the German “nun” (“I have no classes 